{"title_page": "1898 South East Durham by-election", "text_new": "The '''1898 [[South East Durham (UK Parliament constituency)|South East Durham]] [[by-election]]''' was held on 3 February 1898 after the death of the incumbent [[Liberal Unionist]] MP, Sir [[Sir Henry Havelock-Allan, 1st Baronet|Henry Marshman Havelock-Allan]]. The seat was gained by the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] candidate, [[Joseph Richardson (1830\u20131902)|Joseph Richardson]], although the unsuccessful [[Liberal Unionist]] candidate [[Frederick Lambton, 4th Earl of Durham|Frederick William Lambton]] would regain the seat for the Liberal Unionists in the [[1900 UK general election|1900 general election]].\n[[File:Joseph_Richardson.jpg|thumb|120px|Richardson]]\n{{Election box begin | title=South East Durham by-election, 1898<ref name=\"Year Book\">[https://archive.org/details/constitutionaly07unkngoog The Constitutional Year Book], 1904, published by [[Conservative Central Office]], page 143 (167 in web page), Durham</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Liberal Party (UK)\n |candidate = [[Joseph Richardson (1830\u20131902)|Joseph Richardson]]\n |votes = 6,286\n |percentage = \n |change = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Liberal Unionist Party\n |candidate = [[Frederick Lambton, 4th Earl of Durham|Frederick William Lambton]]\n |votes = 6,011\n |percentage = \n |change = \n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n |votes = \n |percentage = \n |change = \n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n |votes = \n |percentage = \n |change = \n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link|\n  |winner     = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |loser      = Liberal Unionist Party\n  |swing      = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{By-elections to the 26th UK Parliament}}\n\n[[Category:By-elections to the Parliament of the United Kingdom in County Durham constituencies|Durham, South East]]\n", "text_old": "The '''1898 [[South East Durham (UK Parliament constituency)|South East Durham]] [[by-election]]''' was held on 3 February 1898 after the death of the incumbent [[Liberal Unionist]] MP, Sir [[Sir Henry Havelock-Allan, 1st Baronet|Henry Marshman Havelock-Allan]]. The seat was gained by the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] candidate, [[Joseph Richardson (1830\u20131902)|Joseph Richardson]], although the unsuccessful [[Liberal Unionist]] candidate [[Frederick Lambton, 4th Earl of Durham|Frederick William Lambton]] would regain the seat for the Liberal Unionists in the [[1900 UK general election|1900 general election]].\n[[File:Joseph_Richardson.jpg|thumb|120px|Richardson]]\n{{Election box begin | title=South East Durham by-election, 1898<ref name=\"Year Book\">[https://archive.org/details/constitutionaly07unkngoog The Constitutional Year Book], 1904, published by [[Conservative Central Office]], page 143 (167 in web page), Durham</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Liberal Party (UK)\n |candidate = [[Joseph Richardson (1830\u20131902)|Joseph Richardson]]\n |votes = 6,286\n |percentage = \n |change = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Liberal Unionist Party\n |candidate = [[Frederick Lambton, 4th Earl of Durham|Frederick William Lambton]]\n |votes = 6,011\n |percentage = \n |change = \n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n |votes = \n |percentage = \n |change = \n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n |votes = \n |percentage = \n |change = \n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link|\n  |winner     = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |loser      = Liberal Unionist Party\n  |swing      = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{By-elections to the 26th UK Parliament}}\n\n[[Category:By-elections to the Parliament of the United Kingdom in County Durham constituencies]]\n", "name_user": "MSGJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "+sort key", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1898_South_East_Durham_by-election"}
