|}\n\n==Harman-Ising Studio films (1934\u20131938)==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Release Date\n! Series\n! Title\n! Director\n! Notes\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| September 1, 1934 || [[Happy Harmonies]] || ''The Discontented Canary'' || [[Rudolf Ising]] ||First cartoon produced by Harman-Ising Pictures for MGM.<br />Initially released as a \"Metro Color Cartoon\", later prints billing it as part of the ''Happy Harmonies'' series.<br />Filmed in [[Technicolor]].\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| September 29, 1934 || Happy Harmonies || ''The Old Pioneer'' || Rudolf Ising ||First cartoon to label the name Happy Harmony on the title.<br />Banned from television because of racial stereotypes towards Indians.<br />Filmed in Technicolor.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| October 27, 1934 || Happy Harmonies || ''Tales of the Vienna Woods'' || [[Hugh Harman]] ||Filmed in Technicolor.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| November 24, 1934 || Happy Harmonies || ''Bosko's Parlor Pranks'' || Hugh Harman ||[[Bosko]]'s first appearance in an MGM cartoon.<br />Filmed in Technicolor.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| December 22, 1934 || Happy Harmonies || ''Toyland Broadcast'' || Rudolf Ising ||Banned from television due to black stereotypes. Was previously shown heavily edited before the ban and survives uncut on home video.<br />Filmed in Technicolor.<br />First MGM cartoon animated by [[Carl Urbano]].\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| January 9, 1935 || [[Happy Harmonies]] || ''Hey-Hey Fever'' || [[Hugh Harman]] ||Last appearance of the original [[Bosko]].\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| February 16, 1935 || Happy Harmonies || ''When the Cat's Away'' || [[Rudolf Ising]] ||First appearance of Little Cheeser, though the character was named only in publicity.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| March 9, 1935 || Happy Harmonies || ''The Lost Chick'' || Hugh Harman ||\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| March 30, 1935 || Happy Harmonies || ''[[The Calico Dragon]]'' ([[File:Award-star-silver-3d.png|15px|Academy Award nomination]]) || Rudolf Ising ||First MGM cartoon to be nominated for an [[Academy Award for Best Animated Short]].\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| April 13, 1935 || Happy Harmonies || ''Good Little Monkeys'' || Hugh Harman ||First of Harman's three \"Good Little Monkeys\" shorts.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| April 27, 1935 || Happy Harmonies || ''The Chinese Nightingale'' || Rudolf Ising ||Banned from television because of racial stereotypes towards Asians.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| May 11, 1935 || Happy Harmonies || ''Poor Little Me'' || Hugh Harman ||\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| May 25, 1935 || Happy Harmonies || ''Barnyard Babies'' || Rudolf Ising ||Last MGM cartoon in 2-strip Technicolor.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| September 21, 1935 || Happy Harmonies || ''The Old Plantation'' || Rudolf Ising ||First cartoon in 3-strip Technicolor not released by Disney.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| October 19, 1935 || Happy Harmonies || ''[[Honeyland (1935 film)|Honeyland]]'' || Rudolf Ising ||\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| November 16, 1935 || Happy Harmonies || ''Alias St. Nick'' || Rudolf Ising ||A Little Cheeser cartoon, though the character is still unnamed on-screen.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| December 14, 1935 || Happy Harmonies || ''Run, Sheep, Run!'' || Hugh Harman ||First appearance of the revamped Bosko.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| January 11, 1936 || [[Happy Harmonies]] || ''[[Bottles (film)|Bottles]]'' || [[Hugh Harman]] ||\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| February 8, 1936 || Happy Harmonies || ''The Early Bird and the Worm'' || [[Rudolf Ising]] ||First appearance of the \"Lazy Crows\".\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| March 7, 1936 || Happy Harmonies || ''[[The Old Mill Pond]]'' ([[File:Award-star-silver-3d.png|15px|Academy Award nomination]]) || Hugh Harman ||First appearance of the \"Jazz Frogs\".\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| April 4, 1936 || Happy Harmonies || ''Two Little Pups'' || Rudolf Ising ||First appearance of the \"Two Little Pups\"<br />Final appearance of the \"Lazy Crows\".\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| May 2, 1936 || Happy Harmonies || ''The Old House'' || Hugh Harman ||Featuring [[Bosko]].\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| May 30, 1936 || Happy Harmonies || ''The Pups' Picnic'' || Rudolf Ising ||Featuring the \"Two Little Pups\".\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| June 4, 1936 || Happy Harmonies || ''To Spring'' || [[William Hanna]] ||William Hanna's directorial debut.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| July 11, 1936 || Happy Harmonies || ''Little Cheeser'' || Rudolf Ising ||Third appearance of Little Cheeser, and the first cartoon to name him on-screen.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| December 12, 1936 || Happy Harmonies || ''The Pups' Christmas'' || Rudolf Ising ||Featuring the \"Two Little Pups\".\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| January 16, 1937 || [[Happy Harmonies]] || ''Circus Daze'' || [[Hugh Harman]] ||Featuring [[Bosko]]<br />Last cartoon billed as a Happy Harmony. However, the remaining Harman-Ising shorts of this period are considered as part of the series.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| February 13, 1937 || Happy Harmonies || ''[[Swing Wedding]]'' || Hugh Harman ||Featuring the \"Jazz Frogs\".\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| March 20, 1937 || Happy Harmonies || ''Bosko's Easter Eggs'' || Hugh Harman ||Bosko's final solo cartoon.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| May 1, 1937 || Happy Harmonies || ''Little Ol' Bosko and the Pirates'' || Hugh Harman ||First of three cartoons pairing Bosko with the \"Jazz Frogs\".\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| May 29, 1937 || Happy Harmonies || ''The Hound and the Rabbit'' || [[Rudolf Ising]] ||\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| July 10, 1937 || Happy Harmonies || ''The Wayward Pups'' || Rudolf Ising ||Final appearance of the \"Little Pups\".\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: right\"| August 