}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/282559|title=True Blue: Ve Skerries, Atlantic|website=[[Canmore (database)|Canmore]]|url-status=live|access-date=2020-04-06|ref={{harvid|Canmore - True Blue|}}}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/239832|title=Turquoise: Ve Skerries, Atlantic|website=[[Canmore (database)|Canmore]]|url-status=live|access-date=2020-04-06|ref={{harvid|Canmore - Turquoise|}}}}\n*{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=June 1930|title=Two Wrecks in the Shetlands|url=https://rnliarchive.blob.core.windows.net/media/1312/0302.pdf#page=14|format=PDF|journal=The Lifeboat|volume=XXVIII|pages=66-69|ref={{harvid|The Lifeboat|1930}}|via=RNLI Archive}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/290649|title=Unknown: Ve Skerries, Atlantic - Whaler (17th Century)(Possible)|website=[[Canmore (database)|Canmore]]|url-status=live|access-date=2020-04-07|ref={{harvid|Canmore - Unknown 1602|}}|date=|last=|first=|archive-url=|archive-date=}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/290642|title=Unknown: Ve Skerries, Atlantic - Barque (19th Century)|website=[[Canmore (database)|Canmore]]|url-status=live|access-date=2020-04-07|ref={{harvid|Canmore - Unknown 1880 (2)|}}|date=|last=|first=|archive-url=|archive-date=}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/290641|title=Unknown: Ve Skerries, Atlantic - Craft (18th Century)|website=[[Canmore (database)|Canmore]]|url-status=live|access-date=2020-04-07|ref={{harvid|Canmore - Unknown 1725 (2)|}}|date=|last=|first=|archive-url=|archive-date=}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/290638|title=Unknown: Ve Skerries, Atlantic - Craft (18th Century)|website=[[Canmore (database)|Canmore]]|url-status=live|access-date=2020-04-07|ref={{harvid|Canmore - Unknown 1762 (2)|}}|date=|last=|first=|archive-url=|archive-date=}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/290639|title=Unknown: Ve Skerries, Atlantic - Craft (18th Century)|website=[[Canmore (database)|Canmore]]|url-status=live|access-date=2020-04-07|ref={{harvid|Canmore - Unknown 1748 (2)|}}|date=|last=|first=|archive-url=|archive-date=}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/290648|title=Unknown: Ve Skerries, Atlantic - Craft (19th Century)|website=[[Canmore (database)|Canmore]]|url-status=live|access-date=2020-04-07|ref={{harvid|Canmore - Unknown 1883|}}|date=|last=|first=|archive-url=|archive-date=}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/290646|title=Unknown: Ve Skerries, Atlantic - Craft (19th Century)|website=[[Canmore (database)|Canmore]]|url-status=live|access-date=2020-04-07|ref={{harvid|Canmore - Unknown 1892 (2)|}}|date=|last=|first=|archive-url=|archive-date=}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/329303|title=Unknown 1725|website=[[Canmore (database)|Canmore]]|url-status=live|access-date=2020-04-07|ref={{harvid|Canmore - Unknown 1725 (1)|}}|date=|last=|first=|archive-url=|archive-date=}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/329315|title=Unknown 1748|website=[[Canmore (database)|Canmore]]|url-status=live|access-date=2020-04-07|ref={{harvid|Canmore - Unknown 1748 (1)|}}|date=|last=|first=|archive-url=|archive-date=}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/329368|title=Unknown 1762|website=[[Canmore (database)|Canmore]]|url-status=live|access-date=2020-04-07|ref={{harvid|Canmore - Unknown 1762 (2)|}}|date=|last=|first=|archive-url=|archive-date=}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/329284|title=Unknown 1880|website=[[Canmore (database)|Canmore]]|url-status=live|access-date=2020-04-07|ref={{harvid|Canmore - Unknown 1880 (1)|}}|date=|last=|first=|archive-url=|archive-date=}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/325412|title=Unknown 1892|website=[[Canmore (database)|Canmore]]|url-status=live|access-date=2020-04-07|ref={{harvid|Canmore - Unknown 1892 (1)|}}|date=|last=|first=|archive-url=|archive-date=}}\n*{{Cite web|url=http://www.nlb.org.uk/LighthouseLibrary/Lighthouse/Ve-Skerries/|title=Ve Skerries|date=2009|website=[[Northern Lighthouse Board]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140521220014/http://www.nlb.org.uk/LighthouseLibrary/Lighthouse/Ve-Skerries/|archive-date=21 May 2014|access-date=21 May 2014|ref={{harvid|NLB|2009}}}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/271453/ve-skerries-beacon|title=Ve Skerries, Beacon|last=|first=|date=|website=Canmore|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-03|ref={{harvid|Canmore|}}}}\n*{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0002442/19090519/078/0004|title=Wreck of a Norwegian Brigantine|date=1909-05-19|work=[[The Orkney Herald|Orkney Herald, and Weekly Advertiser and Gazette for the Orkney & Zetland Islands]]|access-date=2020-04-12|url-status=live|ref={{harvid|Orkney Herald|1909}}|url-access=subscription|via=The [[British Newspaper Archive]]}}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Shetlopedia|page=Ve_Skerries}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.nlb.org.uk/LighthouseLibrary/Main/ Northern Lighthouse Board] \n* [http://www.nlb.org.uk/uploadedImages/Images/Lighthouse_Library/Ve%20Skerries.jpg Picture of Ve Skerries Lighthouse]\n\n{{Shetland}}\n{{Lighthouses of the Northern Lighthouse Board}}\n\n[[Category:Uninhabited islands of Shetland]]\n[[Category:Skerries of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Archipelagoes of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Underwater diving sites in Scotland]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Papa Stour Shtl.png|right|thumb|270px|Map of the Ve Skerries]]\nThe '''Ve Skerries''' or '''Vee Skerries'''{{sfn|The Lifeboat|1930|p=66}} ({{lang-non|Vestan sker}}, West Skerries) are a group of low [[Skerry|skerries]] {{convert|3|mi|spell=in}} north west of [[Papa Stour]], on the west coast of [[Shetland]], Scotland. They define the southwest perimeter of [[St Magnus Bay]].{{sfn|OS Name Book|1878|p=3}}\n\n==Skerries==\nThe individual skerries are named:\n\n* North Skerry\n* Ormal ({{Lang-nrn|ormel}} - remnant or fragment){{sfn|Jakobsen|1928|p=640}}\n* The Clubb ([[Shetland dialect]]: hill square in shape,{{sf|Jakobsen|1897|p=78}} from {{Lang-nrn|klobb}} - crag or rugged hill-top){{sfn|Jakobsen|1928|p=433}}\n* Reaverack\n* Helligoblo\n\n==Wrecks==\nDue to the low depth of water in the vicinity, and unpredictable currents, the Ve Skerries are notorious for their danger to passing ships.{{sfn|The Lifeboat|1930|p=66}} Many ships throughout history have wrecked on the rocks.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Wrecks on the Ve Skerries\n!Vessel\n!From\n!Type\n!Date wrecked\n!Casualties\n!Ref\n|-\n|Unknown{{Efn|Presumed to have wrecked on the Ve Skerries|name=presumed|group=}}\n|\n|[[Whaler]]\n|1602\n|\n|{{sfn|Canmore - Unknown 1602|}}\n|-\n|Unknown\n|\n|\n|1725\n|\n|{{sfn|Canmore - Unknown 1725 (1)|}}{{sfn|Canmore - Unknown 1725 (2)|}}\n|-\n|Unknown\n|\n|\n|1748\n|\n|{{sfn|Canmore - Unknown 1748 (1)|}}{{sfn|Canmore - Unknown 1748 (2)|}}\n|-\n|Unknown\n|\n|\n|data-sort-value=\"1762\"|{{Circa|1762}}\n|\n|{{Sfn|Canmore - Unknown 1762 (1)|}}{{Sfn|Canmore - Unknown 1762 (2)|}}\n|-\n|''True Blue''\n|{{Flagicon|England}} [[Liverpool]]\n|[[Brig]]\n|data-sort-value=\"1850\"|\u2264 1850\n|Full crew killed\n|{{sfn|Canmore - True Blue|}}{{Sfn|Robertson|1848|p=}}\n|-\n|''Turquoise''\n|{{flag|Shetland|civil}}\n|[[Cutter (boat)|Cutter]]\n|data-sort-value=\"1872-10-02\"|2 October 1872\n|Full crew killed\n|{{sfn|Canmore - Turquoise|}}\n|-\n|Unknown{{Efn|name=presumed}}\n|\n|[[Barque]]\n|data-sort-value=\"1880-10-30\"|30 October 1880\n|\n|{{sfn|Canmore - Unknown 1880 (1)|}}{{sfn|Canmore - Unknown 1880 (2)|}}\n|-\n|Unknown{{Efn|name=presumed}}\n|\n|\n|data-sort-value=\"1883-09\"|September 1883\n|\n|{{sfn|Canmore - Unknown 1883|}}\n|-\n|''Nor''\n|{{Flagicon|Norway}} [[Arendal]]\n|Barque\n|data-sort-value=\"1892-01-03\"|3 January 1892\n|Full crew of 8 killed\n|{{sfn|Canmore - Nor|}}\n|-\n|Unknown\n|\n|Barque\n|1892\n|\n|{{Sfn|Canmore - Unknown 1892(1)|}}{{Sfn|Canmore - Unknown 1892(2)|}}\n|-\n|[[SV Illeri|''Illeri'']]\n|{{Flagicon|Norway}} [[Sandefjord]]\n|Brig{{Efn|Originally built as a [[brigantine]] but modified to a brig in 1907{{sfn|Lettens|2017}}|name=|group=}}\n|data-sort-value=\"1909-05-09\"|9 May 1909\n|0\n|{{sfn|Canmore - Illeri|}}\n|-\n|''[[SS Ben Doran|Ben Doran]]''\n|{{Flagicon|Scotland}} [[Aberdeen]]\n|[[Steamship|Steam]] [[Fishing trawler|trawler]]\n|data-sort-value=\"1930-03-29\"|29 March 1930\n|Full crew of ~9 killed\n|{{sfn|Canmore - Ben Doran|}}\n|-\n|[[MFV Elinor Viking|''Elinor Viking'']]\n|{{Flagicon|Scotland}} Aberdeen\n|[[Diesel engine|Diesel]] trawler\n|data-sort-value=\"1977-12-09\"|9 December 1977\n|0\n|{{sfn|Canmore - Elinor Viking|}}\n|-\n|''[[MV Coelleira|Coelleira]]''\n|{{Flagicon|Scotland}} [[Oban|Oban]]{{efn|Vessel was Spanish-owned, but registered in the UK{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=1}}}}\n|Fishing vessel\n|data-sort-value=\"2019-08-04\"|4 August 2019\n|0\n|{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=2}}\n|}\n{{notelist}}\n\n===''Illeri''===\n{{Main|SV Illeri}}\nWhile travelling between the [[Faroe Islands]] and [[Leith]] in [[ballast]] under the command of Captain Samuelson, ''Illeri'' went aground on the northeast end{{sfn|Canmore - Illeri|}} of the [[Ve Skerries]], [[Shetland]] early in the morning of Sunday 5 May 1919 due to poor visibility in thick fog. The conditions were calm enough to allow the crew to consider abandoning ship in a smaller boat kept aboard. When the ship started breaking up, the ship's papers were gathered and it was was abandoned.{{sfn|Shetland Times|1909}} The boat was directed to [[Muckle Roe]], where they were redirected to Olnafirth where the Norwegian Olna Whaling Station was based, to which they safely arrived.{{sfn|Orkney Herald|1909}}\n\nOn the same morning, a report from [[Sandness]] reached Divisional Officer Mr Rogers at [[Fort Charlotte, Shetland|Fort Charlotte]], [[Lerwick]] that the ship had wrecked.{{sfn|Shetland Times|1909}} He summoned the [[Northern Lighthouse Board|Northern Lighthouse Commissioners']] [[steamship]] ''Pole Star'' (which was leaving port) by [[Flag semaphore|semaphore]] to return and conveyed the report to the chief officer. ''Pole Star'' then proceeded to the Ve Skerries, where they found the ship waterlogged and abandoned. The ships' state indicated it had been quickly abandoned - [[The Orkney Herald]] reported that \"they found the sails merely clued up, but not stowed, the side lights burning, and a 24 hour alarm timepiece lying on the cabin table still going.\" They were able to retrieve more of the ship's papers still aboard the vessel, which were passed on to the [[Receiver of Wreck|Reciever of Wreck]] in [[Scalloway]]. The following day ''Pole Star'' learned the crew had arrived in Olnafirth while delivering supplies to Muckle Roe.{{sfn|Orkney Herald|1909}}\n\nSome of the ''Illeri'' crew (including the captain) visited the wreck again on Monday 6 May, however the ship was by then \"a total wreck\". The crew were forwarded on to Lerwick on Tuesday 7 May, and were then sent by the Norwegian Consul to Leith aboard SS ''Queen'' on Thursday 9 May''.{{sfn|Shetland Times|1909}}''\n\n===''Ben Doran''===\n{{Main|SS Ben Doran}}\nOn 29 March 1930, the [[Aberdeen]] [[Steamship|steam]] [[Fishing trawler|trawler]] [[SS Ben Doran|''Ben Doran'']] ran aground on the north end of Heligoblo{{sfn|Canmore - Ben Doran|}} in bad weather and rough sea conditions, due in part to poor coverage in nautical charts of the area, and lack of knowledge of the tides around the shallow reef surrounding the Ve Skerries which were considered unpredictable even to experienced Shetland fishermen. Another passing trawler brought news of the accident to [[Lerwick]] by 5pm,{{sfn|The Lifeboat|1930|p=66}} after which the [[Stromness]] Lifeboat Station in [[Orkney]] was notified, and [[Board of Trade|Board of Trade's]] life-saving apparatus - a rocket propelled rope to shoot to another vessel, to allow for it to be towed to safety{{sfn|SSVLB|}} - was arranged and taken by lorry to [[Ronas Voe]]. The apparatus was taken aboard the steam trawler ''Arora'' and it departed towards the Ve Skerries at 2am on 30 March.{{sfn|The Lifeboat|1930|p=66}}\n\nHonorary Secretary of the [[Royal National Lifeboat Institution|RNLI]]'s Lerwick branch, George Theodore Kay,{{sfn|Gott|2008}} who was aware of the geography of the Ve Skerries, thought that a ship the size of ''Arora'' would struggle to come close enough to ''Ben Doran'' to effect a rescue attempt. He learned that a smaller motor boat named ''Smiling Morn'' was berthed in [[Voe, Delting]], and suggested that this vessel accompanied by a four-oared rowing boat would have a better chance at success. He, with John Falconer, master of the trawler ''Boscobell'', and W. H. Dougall from [[The Mission to Seafarers|The Missions to Seamen]] proceeded to Voe and enrolled the assistance of ''Smiling Morn''.{{sfn|The Lifeboat|1930|p=66-67}} They headed for Housa Voe, [[Papa Stour]] to procure the expertise of someone there with experience of the seabed around the Ve Skerries. By entering Housa Voe in rough conditions and during the night, they themselves nearly collided with a sunken rock. Upon landfall in Housa Voe they enlisted the assistance of John Henderson, and headed towards the Ve Skerries.{{sfn|The Lifeboat|1930|p=67}}\n\n''Smiling Morn'' arrived before 5am at the Ve Skerries, which ''Arora'' had reached first. Heavy seas and high winds continued and proved to make a very difficult rescue attempt. Five of ''Ben Doran'''s crew were seen clinging to the ship's [[rigging]] while [[sea spray]] hit them. ''Arora'' made an approach, however they only reached in far enough that their crew thought that they would not be able to return to safety, and still ''Ben Doran'' was out of reach. Retreating, they relayed that an additional two crewmembers were spotted in the rigging. ''Ben Doran''<nowiki/>'s position in the middle of the skerries (being {{convert|600|yd|m}} west from the nearest skerry) meant there was no plausible means of rescue, owing to the shallow reef surrounding it. Kay, who examined the area 2 months later, commented that it was \"abundantly clear that rescue would have been hopeless.\"{{sfn|The Lifeboat|1930|p=67}}\n\nAt one point a \"tide lump\" ([[Shetland dialect]]: a rapid escalation of tidal activity){{sfn|Graham|2010b}} fell into the {{convert|20|ft|m|abbr=|adj=on}} rowing boat which ''Smiling Morn'' had in tow, and it sunk. ''Smiling Morn''{{'}}s skipper, John Jamieson, was adamant in attempting a rescue despite the danger to his own crew, and due to this a fight nearly broke out upon the ship, leading the rest of the crew to tie him up to keep him from doing so. Despite the effort put in by the crew of each of the would-be rescue vessels, they resolved that nothing more could be done and so they abandoned the rescue.{{sfn|The Lifeboat|1930|p=67}}\n[[File:In_Melby_Cemetery.jpg|alt=|thumb|Tombstones dedicated the crew of ''Ben Doran'' in the [[Melby, Shetland|Melby]] Cemetery]]\nThe Stromness Lifeboat Station was alerted to the unsuccessful attempt by 4pm 30 March. By 4:45pm the Stromness Lifeboat departed, reaching Scalloway by 7:30am on 31 March. By the time the lifeboat arrived at the Ve Skerries, only the gallows for supporting the ship's anchor could be seen.{{sfn|The Lifeboat|1930|p=69}} All of the nine crew members believed to have been on board were killed.{{sfn|Allen|2018}} The wrecking of ''Ben Doran'' and the deaths of the crew validated the need for a lifeboat to be stationed in Shetland. In 1933 the [[Aith]] Lifeboat Station was opened.{{sfn|RNLI|}}\n\nThe wreck of the ''Ben Doran'' is used as a dive site for sport divers and underwater photographers.{{sfn|Shetland.org|}}\n\n===''Elinor Viking''===\n{{Main|MFV Elinor Viking}}\nOn the 9th December 1977 [[MFV Elinor Viking|''Elinor Viking'']], an Aberdeen trawler was wrecked on the east side of Reaverack{{sfn|Canmore - Elinor Viking|}} due to extreme weather conditions. The Aith Lifeboat was sent to the scene, however due to the wreck's position it was not able to get close enough to the vessel to transfer to the crew to safety. Both of the ship's liferafts had been swept away by the sea, and the ship had been breached and lay half-filled with water. An appeal was made to [[Sumburgh Airport]] where [[British Airways]] had helicopters stationed, and a volunteer crew was assembled,{{sfn|Reardon Smith|1978}} including Captain George Bain as the chief pilot, and Major Alasdair Campbell as a [[Winch|winchman]].{{sfn|Telegraph|2012}}\n\nThey reached the scene within about an hour and, with the aid of another helicopter and an [[Royal Air Force|RAF]] [[Hawker Siddeley Nimrod|Nimrod]] trying to provide light in the dark conditions, they proceeded with the rescue attempt in horrendous weather. The light coming from dropped flares from the Nimrod was deemed impossible to time correctly with the winch lowering, such that their only effective source of light was the helicopter's landing lights. ''Elinor Viking'' had developed considerable list as it began to sink. Campbell, upon his first attempt being lowered down to the ship, was unexpectedly swayed and his cable became caught in the mast of the ship. The risk of losing the helicopter meant that the winch operator nearly took the decision to sever the cable to Campbell, however he was able to be retrieved back into the helicopter and immediately offered to be lowered again. Using a rock which was repeatedly out of view with the swell as the best reference, Bain was able to keep the aircraft steady to continue the rescue. Through the following hour and twenty minutes, lowering approximately twelve times, Campbell was able to hoist up the crew.{{sfn|London Gazette|1978|p=8046}} The last to leave the ship was the skipper, who (either through hypothermia or shock) could not let go of the ships railing, requiring Bain to hit him to continue the rescue.{{sfn|Telegraph|2012}}\n\nDespite the crew of the helicopter not being trained for rescue work, all 8 of ''Elinor Viking's'' crew were successfully winched to safety.{{sfn|Reardon Smith|1978}} Both Bain and Campbell received [[Queen's Gallantry Medal|Queen's Gallantry Medals]] for \"outstanding bravery, skill and determination in conditions of extreme weather and darkness operating in a situation far beyond that normally expected of a helicopter on rescue service.\"{{sfn|London Gazette|1978|p=8046}}\n\n===''Coelleira''===\n{{Main|MV Coelleira}}\n[[File:Coelleira wrecked on the Clubb, Ve Skerries pre salvage attempt.jpg|thumb|''Coelleira'' aground on the Clubb before the salvage attempt]]\nLate on 3 August 2019, the UK-registered, Spanish-owned fishing vessel [[MV Coelleira|''Coelleira'']] was returning to [[Scrabster]] from about {{Convert|18|nmi|km mi|abbr=}} north of [[Yell Sound]]'s entrance{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=2}} with a catch of approximately 15 tonnes of fish.{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=4}} Apart from the low light, the conditions were ideal - there was clear visibility, smooth seas and light winds. With the intention of returning as quickly as possible (due to unexpected delays in their fishing operations), the ship's mate set the vessel on a heading of 184\u00b0 and proceeded at a speed of {{convert|9|kn|km/h mph|abbr=}} to keep close to the coast in order to save time. At 21:42 the heading was set to 204\u00b0.{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=2}}\n\nAt 22:30 the skipper (a 56-year-old Spanish national){{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=7}} took over watch from the mate, who went to bed. The skipper over the next 2 hours made five adjustments to the ships' heading in order to follow the coast. The skipper during this time worked on fish landing records and other managerial work. It is not known how often the vessel's position was checked.{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=2}}\n\nAt 00:23 on 4 August, vessel was set to heading of 206\u00b0 with the aim of keeping around {{Convert|3.5|nmi|km mi|abbr=}} away from any navigational risk. The skipper did not see any hazards on the [[chartplotter]], and while he did see a [[lighthouse]] light towards the port bow, he assumed it was a lighthouse on the mainland.{{sfn|MAIB|2020}}\n\nAt an unspecified time, the skipper left the [[Bridge (nautical)|wheelhouse]], and (according to a [[Marine Accident Investigation Branch]] report) while the skipper was returning to his post at 01:24, ''Coelleira'' ran aground on the Clubb travelling at {{convert|10|kn|km/h mph|abbr=}}. The crew awoke with the sound of the collision, whereupon they assembled in the wheelhouse and donned [[Survival suit|survival suits]] and [[life jackets]]. Two lifeboats were launched off the starboard side.{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=2}} At 01:29 the Shetland [[Her Majesty's Coastguard|Coastguard]] were notified of the accident, and in response the [[Aith]] lifeboat and a rescue helicopter were sent to the scene. All 15{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=12}} crew were winched aboard the helicopter, and were returned to [[Lerwick]] uninjured.{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=4}}\n[[File:Coelleira wrecked on the Clubb, Ve Skerries post salvage attempt.jpg|left|thumb|''Coelleira'' on its port side after the salvage attempt]]\nAttempts were subsequently made to refloat the vessel. The ship was surveyed with assistance from the [[Sullom Voe Terminal]] tug ''Tystie'', however during the inspection the vessel rolled 5-10\u00b0 to port, at which point the men aboard were evacuated.{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=4-5}} The emergency towing vessel ''Ievoli Black'' attempted to pull ''Coelleira'' off the Clubb on 7 August, however during the attempt the ship tilted over 55\u00b0 to port, and with a forecast of poor sea conditions and weather the ship was deemed unsalvageable. In the following days the ship broke up and sank.{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=5}}\n\nIn its report on the incident, the [[Marine Accident Investigation Branch]] concluded that the planning of the passage between the fishing grounds and Scrabster was inadequate, the ship's position was not kept track of, and bridge was empty when the ship went aground. They posed that the skipper's decision making may have been impacted by fatigue, while the set up of the bridge's controls may have made it more difficult to observe risks to the ship.{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=1}}\n\n== Ve Skerries Lighthouse ==\n{{Infobox lighthouse\n| item = Q33061460\n| name = Ve Skerries lighthouse\n| image = \n| image_name = \n| caption = \n| location = Ve Skerries<br> [[Papa Stour]]<br> [[Shetland]]<br>[[Scotland]]<br>[[United Kingdom]]\n| pushpin_map = Scotland Shetland\n| relief = 1\n| pushpin_map_caption = Shetland\n| pushpin = lighthouse\n| coordinates = {{coord|60.373129|-1.812250|display=inline,title}}\n| yearbuilt = 1979\n| yearlit = \n| automated = 1979\n| yeardeactivated = \n| foundation = \n| construction = concrete tower\n| shape = cylindrical tower with double balcony and lantern\n| marking = white tower and lantern\n| height = {{convert|14.6|m|ft|0}}\n| focalheight = {{convert|17|m|ft|0}}\n| lens = \n| currentlens = \n| lightsource = batteries power\n| intensity = \n| range = {{convert|11|mi|km|0}}\n| characteristic = Fl (2) W20s.\n| fogsignal = \n| admiralty = A3847\n| NGA = 3556\n| ARLHS = SCO-253\n| managingagent = Northern Lighthouse Board{{sfn|Rowlett|}}\n{{sfn|NLB|2009}}\n}}\n\nThis modern lighthouse on the west side of Ormal was erected following the loss of ''Elinor Viking''. It replaced a lighted buoy itself put in place after the loss of ''Ben Doran.''{{sfn|Canmore|}} The tower is anchored to the rock with 18 steel bars. Built by engineer R. J. MacKay, it was first lit on 27 September 1979. It is not open to the public; its exposed location makes landings by sea difficult.{{sfn|NLB|2009}}\n\n== Folklore ==\nFollowing his tour of Shetland, [[Samuel Hibbert-Ware|Samuel Hibbert]] reported that the Ve Skerries were recounted by Shetlanders as being a retreat of the \"[[Haaf-fish]]\" (more commonly known as selkies) - creatures that would take the appearance of seal, but could take off their skins and would appear human, allowing them to fraternise on land.{{sfn|Hibbert|1822|p=567}} Because [[Seal hunting|seal clubbing]] was (in the past) practised, and because seals would tend to lie on the Ve Skerries, the islanders of [[Papa Stour]] would go there to hunt the seals for the purpose of retrieving their skins, and according to these tales, would sometimes end up hunting the selkies.{{sfn|Hibbert|1822|pp=596-567}}\n\nOne such tale attested that a seal hunter in a party of several, after killing and skinning several seals, was caught out by a sudden swell which caused the rest of the group to assemble in their boat, but left him stranded. Despite trying to rescue him, he had to be abandoned due to the worsening weather. Several selkies (in the form of seals) then landed on the Ve Skerries, took off their skins and proceeded to rescue those of their kind who had been clubbed, stunned and skinned by the hunters. Those who had been skinned began to regain consciousness, and expressed their sorrow over the loss of their only way to return home{{sfn|Hibbert|1822|p=568}} (each selkie only possessing a single skin).{{sfn|Hibbert|1822|p=566}} In particular, one selkie named Ollavitinus would not be able to return to his wives and would be imprisoned on land.{{sfn|Hibbert|1822|pp=568-569}} When the stranded hunter was spotted, Ollavitinus' mother Gioga offered to transport him back to Papa Stour as long as he would return her son's skin, which the hunter agreed to. With the weather worsening, the hunter feared he would not be able to hold on to the seal skin of Gioga all the way back, and pleaded to be allowed to cut holes in her skin to which he could hold, to which Gioga complied. The hunter was successfully transported to Akers Geo, Papa Stour, after which he dutifully retrieved Ollavitinus' skin from a skeo (Shetland dialect: a hut of loosely constructed stone for [[Food drying|wind-drying]] meat or fish){{sfn|Graham|2010a}} in Hamnavoe, allowing him to return to the sea and his wives.{{sfn|Hibbert|1822|p=569}}\n\n==See also==\n{{stack|{{Portal|Scottish Islands|Scotland|Engineering}}}}\n\n* [[Papa Stour]]\n* [[St Magnus Bay]]\n* [[Out Skerries]]\n* [[List of lighthouses in Scotland]]\n* [[List of Northern Lighthouse Board lighthouses]]\n* [[SV Illeri|SV ''Illeri'']]\n* [[SS Ben Doran|SS ''Ben Doran'']]\n* [[MFV Elinor Viking|MFV ''Elinor Viking'']]\n* [[MV Coelleira|MV ''Coelleira'']]\n* [[List of shipwrecks of the United Kingdom]]\n* [[Selkie]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?211405|title=FV Ben Doran (A178) (+1930)|last=Tony|first=Allen|date=2018-05-06|website=The Wrecksite|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-05|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite Bayanne|access-date=2020-03-05|id=I108505|individual-first=George Theodore|individual-last=Kay|date=2008-03-02|year=2008|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.shetlanddialect.org.uk/john-j-grahams-shetland-dictionary.php?word=2209|title=skeo|last=Graham|first=John J.|date=2010a|website=Shetland ForWirds|orig-year=1979|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-05|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.shetlanddialect.org.uk/john-j-grahams-shetland-dictionary.php?word=2542|title=Tide-lumps|last=Graham|first=John J.|date=2010b|website=Shetland ForWirds|orig-year=1979|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-07|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Hibbert|first=Samuel|url=https://archive.org/details/adescriptionshe00hibbgoog|title=A Description of the Shetland Islands, Comprising an Account of their Geology, Scenery, Antiquities, and Superstitions|publisher=Archibald Constable and Co|year=1822|isbn=|edition=1st|location=Edinburgh|pages=|ref=harv|author-link=Samuel Hibbert-Ware|via=archive.org}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Jakobsen|first=Jakob|url=https://archive.org/details/anetymodictofthenornlanginshet/|title=An etymological dictionary of the Norn language in Shetland|publisher=David Nutt (A. G. Berry)|others=Printed by S. L. M\u00f8ller, Copenhagen. Foreword by Anna Horsb\u00f6l, n\u00e9e Jakobsen. Originally p